1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
On April 8th, the World Bank told South Asia
to keep doing more industrial policy.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:14,000
They forgot to ask one question.
Can the workers actually be there?

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:16,000
THE HEAT FLOOR

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Every six months, the World Bank publishes
the South Asia Economic Update.

5
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:45,000
The April 2026 edition has a headline number —
growth slowing to 6.3 percent.

6
00:00:45,000 --> 00:01:05,000
South Asia uses industrial policy at roughly
twice the rate of other emerging markets.

7
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:30,000
The sector that creates the most non-farm jobs
isn't manufacturing. It's services.

8
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Here's what the report doesn't measure.

9
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Between 2001 and 2020, India lost roughly
259 billion working hours per year to heat.

10
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:15,000
A 1°C rise in mean temperature
cut net earnings by 16 percent.

11
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:35,000
A 1°C rise in wet-bulb temperature
cut earnings by 19 percent.

12
00:02:35,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Informal-sector workers were 17 times more likely
to lose earnings on heat-stressed days.

13
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Now overlay this on the manufacturing map.

14
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:30,000
In 2021, four economists published a paper
in the Journal of Political Economy.

15
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Hot days reduce within-shift productivity.
Hot days reduce attendance.

16
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Adaptation is real.
Adaptation is incomplete.

17
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
What does industrial policy buy you
if labor is wet-bulb-bounded?

18
00:04:32,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Three redesigns follow.

19
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:15,000
One. Cooling infrastructure
as industrial subsidy.

20
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Two. Follow the jobs engine
into services.

21
00:06:45,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Three. Parametric heat-day insurance
for informal workers.

